      commentary: 'Every creation story you have ever heard begins with something: a god, a word, a void with a shape. This one begins by taking even "nothing" off the table. Neither non-being nor being — the poet refuses both, because both are already concepts, and concepts come later. Whatever preceded everything must precede the categories we would use to describe it, including absence.\n\nThen the verse does what the whole hymn will keep doing: it asks instead of asserts. Four questions in two lines. What stirred? Where? In whose keeping? Was there water? These are not rhetorical flourishes — they are the honest posture of a mind standing at the edge of what can be known, and choosing to stand there rather than fill the silence with an answer. Three thousand years before the philosophy of science taught us to say "we don\'t know" with a straight face, a Vedic poet built a hymn out of it.\n\nNotice, finally, who is asking. Not a skeptic mocking the tradition from outside — this is scripture, chanted in ritual, preserved syllable-perfect for a hundred generations by people who considered it sacred. The tradition itself enshrined the questions. That is the door through which we enter the Vedas on this journey: not "believe this account," but "sit with this question, the way the poets sat with it."'
