      commentary: 'Read the arc of the whole hymn one more time, because the ending only lands with the build-up. Verse six already did something shocking: it ruled out the gods as witnesses — they came after, so they cannot testify. That leaves one candidate: the overseer in the highest heaven, the one watching it all. Surely he knows. The hymn grants it — saḥ aṅga veda, he surely knows — and then, with four closing syllables, takes it back: yadi vā na veda. Or perhaps he does not.\n\nSit with what kind of tradition preserves this. Not a text of doubt smuggled in by rebels — a hymn placed in the tenth mandala of its most sacred collection and chanted for three thousand years. The people who memorized it syllable by syllable, generation after generation, chose to carry a creation account whose final word is uncertainty. That is not weakness of belief. It is a definition of reverence most of the modern world has forgotten: that the largest questions deserve awe, not closure — and that pretending to certainty you do not have is the real irreverence.\n\nThis is also why the Nasadiya is the right first gem for this journey, and why it speaks so directly to our moment. We live amid machines that answer everything instantly and confidently — and a culture that mistakes confidence for knowledge. Here is the oldest scripture on earth modeling the opposite: full-hearted inquiry, held open. The Upanishads we have been studying inherit exactly this posture — the refusal of cheap answers is not their invention; it is their inheritance. It starts here, in seven verses, at the edge of the beginning of everything.'
